(Herman Rubin) wrote:
> 
> In article <wingo-130193131057@90.190.20.24> wingo@apple.com (Tony Wingo) writes:
> >In article <C0t67p.5rq@mentor.cc.purdue.edu>, hrubin@pop.stat.purdue.edu
> >(Herman Rubin) wrote:
> 
> >> >> Believe me, it wasn't obvious to a lot of smart *and* educated people.
> 
> >> It WAS obvious then to anyone who both knew that factoring was difficult
> >> that at least hopefully inverting exponentiation modulo a product of primes
> >> is a difficult as factoring, and was interested in cryptography.  This would
> >> definitely apply to the Rabin method, which is demonstrably as difficult as
> >> factoring.
> 
> >And again I have to ask, If it was so obvious why, over five decades of
> >intensive cryptographic research,  did no one else describe or use it prior
> >to the RSA folks?
> 
> Before that time, it had not been observed that inverting exponentiation
> was hard.  The fact was not known.  There was a small amount of the use
> of number theory in cryptography, but only at the level of an undergraduate
> course.  Were any good number-theorists actively interested?

Right. So they noticed it first.  That, as I have said is the essense of
invention.

> It is still not known how hard factoring is; there has been a continual
> improvement in the process, and if it turns out factoring is MUCH easier,
> the RSA algorithm will become essentially useless.  While it may be shown
> that trap-door functions exist, I am not aware of any definitely shown to
> be so.
> 
> >Note that they are not claiming to patent the fact that factoring or
> >inverting exponentiation is hard, the have simply patented what was at the
> >time a unique and original application of that fact, which is the essense
> >of invention.
> 
> RSA were actively working on the problems of primality testing and factorization
> before they came up with the algorithm.  I have read some of their papers.  

Yeah. So?
 
> >If you want to claim that their invention was not unique and original,
> >you'll demonstrate that someone else used it or described it earlier.  The
> >fact that someone else COULD have come up with it can be said of any
> >invention, so is not in and of itself sufficient.
> 
> The question is, what is obvious?  It depends on the person.  One of the
> jokes going around around 1950 was that "obvious mod von Neumann" meant that
> if you were really bright you might be able to prove the result in two weeks.
> Does "skilled in the art" mean a sign-painter or an artist?  I claim it was
> obvious to any artist looking at the problem.  That nobody had seen it before
> is not inconsistent with that.

But again, that claim can be made about ANY invention after the fact.


-tony

